# =============================================================================
# .clinerules - TB-HITL Specification Standards
# Trial Balance Business Requirements & Lineage Specification
# =============================================================================
# This file defines rules and standards for maintaining the TB-HITL 
# traceability specification to ensure consistency and prevent errors.
# =============================================================================

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# DOCUMENT STANDARDS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Requirement Derivation Rules

When deriving business requirements from source documents:

1. **Always quote source text verbatim**
   - Use italics for quoted text
   - Preserve exact wording from source document
   - Do NOT paraphrase unless explicitly noted

2. **Include precise location references**
   - Format: "TB-BC-001, Section X, Paragraph Y, Page Z (Lines N-M in extracted MD)"
   - Include line numbers from machine-readable extraction when available
   - Reference employee/author ID when known (e.g., "Created by: 1498002")

3. **Use MoSCoW prioritization for ALL requirements**
   - MUST: Non-negotiable for v1.0
   - SHOULD: Important but can slip
   - COULD: Nice to have
   - WON'T: Explicitly out of scope (this phase)

4. **Every requirement needs acceptance criteria**
   - Format: AC-<REQ-ID>-<NUMBER> (e.g., AC-ES01-1, AC-ES01-2)
   - Criteria must be measurable and verifiable
   - Include specific thresholds (numbers, percentages, timeframes)

## Requirement ID Conventions

| Category | Prefix | Example |
|----------|--------|---------|
| Executive Summary | TB-REQ-ES | TB-REQ-ES01 |
| Scope | TB-REQ-SC | TB-REQ-SC01 |
| Process Step | TB-REQ-PS | TB-REQ-PS01 |
| AI Augmentation | TB-REQ-AI | TB-REQ-AI01 |
| BSS Risk Assessment | BSS-REQ | BSS-REQ-01 |

## Citation Format

```latex
\begin{tcolorbox}[colback=sourcegreen!5,colframe=sourcegreen!70,title=Source Quotation]
\textit{``Exact quoted text from source document...''}
\end{tcolorbox}

\begin{tabularx}{\textwidth}{@{}lX@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Attribute} & \textbf{Value} \\
\midrule
\textbf{Requirement ID} & TB-REQ-XXnn \\
\textbf{MoSCoW Priority} & MUST/SHOULD/COULD/WON'T \\
\textbf{Source Document} & Full document name \\
\textbf{Source ID} & TB-BC-001/TB-BPMN-001/etc. \\
\textbf{Source Location} & Section, Paragraph, Page (Lines) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
```

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# SCHEMA STANDARDS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Enum Governance

1. **All shared enums MUST reference docs/schema/common/enums.yaml**
   - Never redefine shared enums locally
   - Use $ref to common definitions
   - Changes require RFC with spec owner approval

2. **Shared enums include:**
   - risk_status (TB + BSS)
   - decision_outcome (TB + Arabic + Regulations)
   - variance_type (TB)
   - workflow_state_type (TB + BSS)
   - audit_action (TB + BSS + Arabic)
   - source_system (TB + Arabic)

3. **Adding new enums:**
   - Submit RFC to Controls Architecture Team
   - 5-day review period
   - All consuming spec owners must approve
   - One-release deprecation window for breaking changes

## JSON Schema Requirements

1. Use JSON Schema Draft 2020-12 or later
2. Every schema MUST include:
   - `$schema` declaration
   - `$id` with unique identifier
   - `title` and `description`
   - `required` array for mandatory fields
   - `additionalProperties: false` to prevent schema drift

3. Field naming conventions:
   - Use snake_case for all fields
   - Prefix audit fields with `audit_` (e.g., `audit_id`, `audit_timestamp`)
   - Suffix identifiers with `_id` (e.g., `persona_id`, `resource_id`)

## Schema File Naming

| Type | Pattern | Example |
|------|---------|---------|
| Record schema | noun-noun.schema.json | variance-record.schema.json |
| Entry schema | noun-entry.schema.json | audit-trail-entry.schema.json |
| Extract schema | noun-extract.schema.json | tb-extract.schema.json |
| Params schema | noun-params.schema.json | entity-params.schema.json |

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# IMPLEMENTATION STANDARDS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

## State Machine (28 States - Authoritative)

**CRITICAL: The authoritative state count is 28, NOT 27.**

States 1-24: Primary workflow states
States 25-27: Error handling states (AWAITING_CLARIFICATION, ESCALATED_TO_FINANCE, MANUAL_OVERRIDE)
State 28: COMPLETED (end state)

All state transitions MUST:
- Be logged to audit trail with timestamp and persona_id
- Include before_state and after_state snapshots
- Use optimistic locking (version field)

## API Response Codes

| Code | Meaning | Use Case |
|------|---------|----------|
| 200 | Success | All items succeeded |
| 207 | Multi-Status | Partial success (bulk operations) |
| 400 | Bad Request | Invalid request body |
| 401 | Unauthorized | Token missing/expired |
| 403 | Forbidden | Insufficient permissions |
| 409 | Conflict | Race condition (item already claimed) |
| 429 | Too Many Requests | Rate limit exceeded |
| 500 | Internal Error | Server-side failure |
| 503 | Service Unavailable | vLLM/backend unavailable |
| 504 | Gateway Timeout | Request timeout |

## Quality Thresholds

| Metric | Target | Kill-Switch Trigger |
|--------|--------|---------------------|
| accept_without_edit_rate | ≥70% | <50% |
| accept_with_any_edit_rate | ≥95% | <85% |
| vLLM availability | ≥95% | <95% |
| vLLM latency P95 | <5000ms | >5000ms |
| vLLM error rate | <10% | >10% |

## Anomaly Detection Thresholds

1. **Normality Test First (Shapiro-Wilk)**
   - If p-value > 0.05: Use Z-score
   - If p-value ≤ 0.05: Use MAD (robust for fat tails)

2. **Thresholds:**
   - Z-score threshold: 3.0
   - MAD threshold: 3.5
   - Spike/drop threshold: 25% period-over-period

## vLLM Fallback Triggers

Switch to template-based commentary when ANY of:
- vLLM latency P95 > 5000ms (5-minute rolling window)
- vLLM error rate > 10% (5-minute rolling window)
- Health check fails 3 consecutive probes

Template confidence capped at 75% (vs LLM typical 85%+)

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# FILE NAMING CONVENTIONS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

## LaTeX Files

| Type | Pattern | Example |
|------|---------|---------|
| Chapters | chapters/XX-name.tex | chapters/04-business-requirements.tex |
| Visual aids | chapters/00-name.tex | chapters/00-visual-traceability-map.tex |
| Fragments | fragment-name.tex | fragment-executive-summary.tex |
| Main doc | spec-name.tex | tb-business-requirements-traceability.tex |
| Merged doc | spec-name-merged.tex | tb-business-requirements-traceability-merged.tex |

## Entity Parameters

- Path: docs/schema/tb/entity-params/<LE-CODE>.yaml
- Example: docs/schema/tb/entity-params/HKG.yaml
- Contents: legal_entity_code, materiality_thresholds, review_config

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AUDIT FINDING RESOLUTION FORMAT
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

When documenting audit findings and resolutions:

```latex
\begin{tcolorbox}[colback=red!5,colframe=red!70,title=\faIcon{exclamation-triangle} Finding ID: Description]
\textbf{Location:} Document reference, page, section \\
\textbf{Issue:} Clear description of the problem \\
\textbf{Impact:} What breaks if not fixed \\
\textbf{Severity:} \textbf{P0/P1/P2} - Critical/High/Medium \\
\textbf{Owner:} Responsible person/team \\
\textbf{Timeline:} X days/weeks
\end{tcolorbox}

\textbf{Resolution:}
\begin{tcolorbox}[colback=green!5,colframe=green!70,title=\faIcon{check-circle} Resolution Applied]
[Detailed resolution with code/schema/config examples]
\end{tcolorbox}
```

## Severity Codes

| Code | Severity | Timeline | Blocks Release? |
|------|----------|----------|-----------------|
| P0 | Critical | 1-2 weeks | Yes |
| P1 | High | 4 weeks | Conditional |
| P2 | Medium | 8 weeks | No |
| P3 | Low | Backlog | No |

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# REVIEW CHECKLIST
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Auditor Validation Points

Before sign-off, verify:

- [ ] All requirements quote source text verbatim
- [ ] Location references are precise (section, paragraph, page, line)
- [ ] Derivation rationale is documented
- [ ] Acceptance criteria are measurable
- [ ] MoSCoW priority is assigned
- [ ] Traceability exceptions are documented (Table 14.X)
- [ ] Shared enums reference enums.yaml (not local definitions)
- [ ] State count is 28 (not 27)
- [ ] Gaps have owners and timelines

## Implementor Ready Criteria

Before starting development, verify:

- [ ] State transition table is embedded (35+ transitions)
- [ ] LLM Service Contract is specified (endpoint, request/response, errors)
- [ ] Bulk operation HTTP codes are defined (200/207/409)
- [ ] UI tech stack is documented (Angular + NgRx + SAP UI5)
- [ ] Entity-params loader spec is complete
- [ ] Anomaly detection thresholds are specified (Z-score + MAD)
- [ ] vLLM fallback triggers are documented
- [ ] Template library (TPL-001 to TPL-007) is specified
- [ ] Audit trail schema exists (audit-trail-entry.schema.json)

## Business Owner Ready Criteria

Before approval, verify:

- [ ] G-001 financial analysis has preliminary ROI estimate
- [ ] ML timeline is caveated (not committed)
- [ ] Commentary quality remediation protocol exists
- [ ] Cross-spec governance is documented
- [ ] Exit gates and kill-switch conditions are defined
- [ ] EUC retirement plan is specified (12-month deprecation)

